.SH NAME
bl \- a simple command‑line utility
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B bl
.RI [ options ] " " [ arguments ...]
.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.B bl
program is a lightweight command‑line tool that performs a basic operation
(such as printing a greeting, processing input, or acting as a placeholder
for a larger application).  It reads its arguments from the command line
and writes its output to standard output.  Errors and diagnostic messages
are written to standard error.
.PP
If no arguments are supplied, the program displays a short usage message.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-h\fR, \fB\-\-help
Show a brief help message and exit.
.TP
.B \-v\fR, \fB\-\-version
Print version information and exit.
.TP
.B \-q\fR, \fB\-\-quiet
Suppress normal output; only error messages are printed.
.TP
.B \-d\fR, \fB\-\-debug
Enable debug output, useful for troubleshooting.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
\fBbl\fR
Run the program with no arguments; displays the default usage message.
.TP
\fBbl Hello World\fR
Pass two arguments; the program will process them according to its
functionality (e.g., printing a greeting).
.TP
\fBbl \-\-quiet input.txt\fR
Process \fIinput.txt\fR while suppressing normal output.
.TP
\fBbl \-\-debug \-\-version\fR
Show version information with debug details.
.SH EXIT STATUS
The program returns a zero exit status on success, and a non‑zero value on
error.
